<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1059,1129,1599]" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">
C o m m e n t s: The species was only recently described from the Greek island Lesbos (
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING V" box="[158,311,1159,1181]" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" pagination="1035 - 1046" refId="ref22489" refString="ASSING V. (2005 g): Two new species and new records of Staphylinidae from the Greek island Lesbos (Insecta: Coleoptera). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 37 (2): 1035 - 1046." type="journal article" year="2005">
ASSING 
<quantity box="[243,311,1159,1181]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.005" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" unit="g" value="2005.0">2005g</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
). A comparative study of the external and sexual characters of the above material and of the 
<typeStatus box="[375,464,1189,1211]" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">holotype</typeStatus>
male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2005" box="[573,670,1189,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lesbia">
<emphasis box="[573,670,1189,1211]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">O. lesbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed some differences between populations (microsculpture, puncturation, shape of median lobe of aedeagus and of spermatheca), but no convincing evidence that they should represent distinct species. The intraspecific variation of the aedeagus and of the – previously unknown – spermatheca are illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[344,460,1308,1330]" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">Figs 72-74</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[524,644,1308,1330]" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">Figs 77-79</figureCitation>
. The species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="(STEPHENS)" baseAuthorityName="STEPHENS" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyptera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">O. brachyptera</emphasis>
(STEPHENS)
</taxonomicName>
, as can be inferred from the highly similar morphology of the aedeagus (shape and internal structures of median lobe, apically bifid ventral process of the median lobe, shape and chaetotaxy of the apical lobe of the paramere, shape of the spermatheca). For comparison, the median lobe of the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName box="[872,1030,1428,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyptera">
<emphasis box="[872,1030,1428,1450]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">O. brachyptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[290,366,1458,1480]" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
. All the specimens seen so far have hind wings of reduced length (approximately 1.5 times as long as elytra and distinctly projecting from under the posterior elytra margins when unfolded). However, the presence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of the abdominal tergite VII, as well as the wide distribution suggest that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2005" box="[196,287,1577,1599]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lesbia">
<emphasis box="[196,287,1577,1599]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="361">O. lesbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be wing-dimorphic.
</paragraph>
